<TITLE> Australia reschedules Bangladesh test series for 2010 </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MELBOURNE, Feb 21 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Australia will host their postponed two-test series against Bangladesh in 2010, Cricket Australia (CA) said on Thursday. Australia called off the series last week because it would have clashed with the Beijing Olympic Games, instead opting to host three one-dayers in Darwin at the end of August and in early September. CA said they reached agreement with the Bangladesh Cricket Board at an International Cricket Council meeting in Malaysia to hold the test series in northern Australia in July and August of 2010. Australia normally hosts international matches in its summer months but has started playing matches in winter because of the warmer climate in the northern cities of Darwin and Cairns. "Through the cooperation of the Bangladesh Cricket Board, we have been able to reschedule the test series between Australia and Bangladesh for the middle of 2010 when both teams have no other obligations under the Future Tours programme," CA's general manager of cricket Michael Brown said in a statement. "We believe the opportunity to play the test series in mid-2010 will attract higher television audiences and a high level of interest in Australia and Bangladesh." Bangladesh had said last week they agreed to this year's tests being scrapped but would prefer to play any future tests in "major cricket venues" away from Darwin or Cairns. Bangladesh played two test matches in the cities on their maiden test tour of Australia in 200
